															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/cybersqyd" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(5336470); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=5336470&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610226574" alt="cybersqyd" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=5336470)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/cybersqyd" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(5336470); return false;" >cybersqyd</a></span> <span class="odate time_1609846505 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">05 Jan 2021 11:35</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4862686">
									

<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">[+]&nbsp;Open&nbsp;for&nbsp;crit</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>See&#8230;my core concern here is that there's not really a sense of consequences/stakes here: like, it's fine to have the ethics committee be secretly be behind this but there's not really a like&#8230;clear feeling of there being a motivation for it, and it doesn't really feel like it leads them to achieve anything or to the reader's understanding of this being significantly changed.</p>
<p>Like, it being a power play to allow the EC to gain an upper hand over the O5 council is fine but there's not really a clear idea of:</p>
<ol>
<li>why the EC wants to do this</li>
<li>whether the EC are actually successful</li>
<li>what the EC are going to do if it is successful</li>
</ol>
<p>My feelings are that if this is to work, you'll likely want to actually make the EC/O5 interplay part of the text because it's the interesting part of this but it's also the part which actually feels like it has stakes; and in turn, you'll need to really consider what the framing is that allows you to do this: it's very possible to have the reader be canonically on one or the other as they read this; and in turn, to have partial information about what the other wants.</p>
<p>I don't think the current framing works because it relies too much on the mystery of this being interesting inherently without you doing anything to show <em>why</em> the mystery matters. This said: it's very possible that this is just my opinion and other reviewers will disagree.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

