			<div class="content" id="post-content-4864527">
									

<p>My apologies for the delay in responding.</p>
<p>I would largely second <span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/cybersqyd" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(5336470); return false;"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=5336470&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610047862" alt="cybersqyd" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=5336470)" /></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/cybersqyd" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(5336470); return false;">cybersqyd</a></span>'s suggestions here. There is a lacking sense of stakes and motivation, and whilst hinting at things and not being explicit can be appropriate at times, it can also leave the overall narrative feeling unsatisfying or lacking in motivation.</p>
<p>Creating an interactive tale is something I would not advise here - integrating the EC/O5 interplay into a single SCP article would not be too much for one article and would give this article the necessary narrative momentum and intrigue to pay-off on the premise appropriately - putting it into an interactive tale would strip the initial article of the necessary narrative heft whilst presenting you with the challenge of creating an interactive tale (which is amongst the most difficult things you can try to do on the site, in my opinion).</p>
<p>The primary problem here is that you've got a premise that is a little derivative of other pieces on the site, and without a narrative to really differentiate itself, it's going to come across as unoriginal and stale. The idea of an EC/O5 interplay is a good one and could create some interesting insight into the internal politics of the Foundation and the conflicting factions therein, but without it, you're going to have a rather meandering narrative that won't really explore the premise or its place in the universe well enough to be interesting, in my opinion. Another narrative could do that, but the primary thing you've got here about discovery and researching theories isn't going to do that because it's simply exploring what the anomaly is rather than how it interacts with the world it inhabits.</p>

